{
  "id": "hard_plus_rayleigh_benard_024",
  "answer": {
    "Problem Formalization": "We consider a two-dimensional rectangular domain [0,L]×[0,H] (with L and H unspecified; typical aspect ratio Γ = L/H is assumed order 1 but not given). The fluid is incompressible and obeys the Boussinesq approximation. Steady-state governing equations (residuals to be minimized) are: continuity R_c = ∂u/∂x + ∂v/∂y = 0; x-momentum R_mx = u ∂u/∂x + v ∂u/∂y + ∂p/∂x - ν (∂²u/∂x² + ∂²u/∂y²) = 0; y-momentum R_my = u ∂v/∂x + v ∂v/∂y + ∂p/∂y - ν (∂²v/∂x² + ∂²v/∂y²) - β g (T - T₀) = 0; energy R_e = u ∂T/∂x + v ∂T/∂y - α (∂²T/∂x² + ∂²T/∂y²) = 0. Here ν is kinematic viscosity, α thermal diffusivity, β thermal expansion coefficient, g gravity magnitude, T₀ a reference temperature (e.g., mean of hot and cold). Boundary conditions: bottom wall (y=0): u=0, v=0, T=T_hot; top wall (y=H): u=0, v=0, T=T_cold; left and right walls (x=0, x=L): u=0, v=0 (no-slip) and adiabatic ∂T/∂n = 0. Note: sidewall thermal condition is not specified; adiabatic is assumed. Pressure uniqueness is enforced by setting p=0 at one point (e.g., bottom-left corner) and additionally imposing zero mean pressure over the domain ∫ p dΩ = 0 as a soft constraint.",
    "Physics Constraints": "Incompressibility (divergence-free velocity), Boussinesq approximation (density variation only in buoyancy term, linear with temperature), steadiness (∂/∂t = 0), imposed temperatures on horizontal walls, no-slip on all walls, zero heat flux on sidewalls. The system couples temperature to momentum via the buoyancy source term in R_my and velocity to energy via the advection term in R_e. No additional data or experimental measurements are provided; the workflow relies purely on physics constraints.",
    "Model Choice": "A fully-connected feedforward neural network (PINN) is chosen. It outputs (u, v, p, T) as functions of (x,y). This architecture is suitable because: (i) it can represent the high-dimensional coupled fields without requiring a grid; (ii) automatic differentiation computes PDE residuals exactly; (iii) boundary conditions can be imposed as soft constraints or embedded via output transformations (e.g., enforcing no-slip and fixed temperatures by multiplying distances-to-walls). A multi-head network with shared hidden layers (8 layers, 64 neurons each, tanh activation) balances expressivity and training stability. The output for pressure is not transformed, leaving the additive constant to be fixed by loss terms.",
    "Training Strategy": "The loss function L = λ_pde L_pde + λ_bc L_bc + λ_press L_press, where L_pde = (1/N) ∑ (R_c² + R_mx² + R_my² + R_e²) over N collocation points (uniformly sampled in domain), L_bc = (1/N_bc) ∑ [(u²+v²) on walls + (T-T_hot)² on bottom + (T-T_cold)² on top + (∂T/∂n)² on sides + pressure zero at reference point], and L_press = (∫ p dΩ)² to fix the constant. Weights are tuned: λ_pde=1, λ_bc=10, λ_press=0.1. Collocation points are sampled via Latin Hypercube with 100k interior points and 10k boundary points per epoch. Optimization: Adam (lr=1e-3) for 5000 steps, then L-BFGS with line search. No data is used; only physics loss. Training is performed in dimensionless form (Prandtl, Rayleigh numbers prescribed) to ensure proper scaling.",
    "Validation Failure Risks": "Overfitting to collocation points is unlikely due to the physics loss; but spectral bias (failure to capture high-frequency features near boundaries) can occur. Boundary layers (thermal and viscous) require dense sampling or adaptive refinement. The heat-transport consistency check computes the vertical heat flux q_y = vT - α ∂T/∂y at bottom and top walls, integrates over x, and requires relative difference |(Q_bottom - Q_top)/Q_bottom| < 1e-3. If this fails, it indicates insufficient resolution, poor loss balance, or incorrect boundary condition enforcement. Other risks include convergence to trivial solutions (e.g., if buoyancy term is too weak) or pressure constant not fully fixed. Mitigations: curriculum training (start with low Ra), adaptive collocation sampling, and learning rate annealing for loss weights."
